Part 1

The oxygen cylinder had a small brass regulator that leaked.

If you stood near the head of the bed, you could hear it.

A tiny, dry hiss.

Like steam escaping a pipe three rooms away.

Vikram had tried to tighten it twice with a spanner he'd borrowed from the driver.

Both times, the sound had stopped for ten minutes, then returned, slightly thinner but unchanged.

Binay Ahuja didn't seem to mind it.

Or perhaps he had simply stopped separating the sound of the room from the sound of his own breathing.

His skin had gone the grey-yellow of old newspaper left in the rain.

"Rohan didn't come today," Binay said.

His voice was barely louder than the regulator's hiss.

"He had site inspections at Nandyal, Papa."

"A site doesn't go anywhere, Vikram."

"There was a concrete issue. He wanted to check it himself."

Binay closed his eyes.

The saline line taped to his forearm was empty. A single bubble of air was trapped near the plastic lock, refusing to move up or down.

"He thinks I don't know," Binay whispered.

"Know what, Papa?"

"That he took that job because he didn't want to sit in your shadow here."

Vikram didn't answer.

He sat on the metal chair near the cupboard.

The room smelled of boiled barley water and the spirit the nurse used to clean the thermometer.

"Let him," Binay said, after a long silence. "It is better to build a small wall yourself than to live in a palace someone else gave you."

---

The phone call came at four in the morning.

It was the family doctor, Dr. Joshi.

He didn't use the words he usually used during his weekly visits.

No *Portal pressure.*

No *Let's see.*

He said: "Vikram. Come."

---

The house in Odisha had two gates.

The main gate was wide, iron-grilled, with two stone pillars that had *Ahuja Villa* engraved in white marble.

The side gate was small, green-painted, leading directly to the kitchen garden.

Vikram used the side gate.

The kitchen was already open. The old cook, Ramu, was sitting on a low wooden stool, cleaning cardamom pods in a brass plate.

He didn't look up when Vikram entered.

"Joshi saab is inside," Ramu said.

His fingers were slow, sorting the black seeds from the green husks.

"He asked for black coffee."

"Is Rohan here?"

"He arrived at three. He is in the study."

Vikram walked down the corridor.

The house felt larger than it had yesterday.

The lights were all on, but they seemed to illuminate only the corners of the rooms, leaving the furniture in a grey, unmoving shade.

Dr. Joshi was standing near the study door, his bag already zipped and placed on the corner table.

He looked at Vikram.

Nodded once.

"Heart stopped at three-forty," he said. "No pain. He simply ceased."

Vikram stood there.

He looked at the doctor's bag.

A black leather bag with a worn handle, the leather peeling near the lock to show the grey fabric underneath.

"Rohan is inside," Joshi said, touching Vikram's arm briefly as he passed. "Talk to him."

---

The study room was cold.

Binay's large teak wood desk was empty except for a brass paperweight shaped like a lion.

Rohan was sitting in the guest chair.

His shoes were covered in red Nandyal dust, a dry crust of it clinging to the welt of his left heel.

He didn't look at Vikram.

"You should have called me earlier," Rohan said.

"I called at midnight. Your phone was switched off."

"The site office has no network after ten. You know that."

"I sent the driver."

"The driver took three hours to reach," Rohan said. His voice was tight, thin, like a wire drawn too straight. "He arrived after the doctor had already signed the certificate."

He stood up.

He walked to the window, looking out at the kitchen garden where Ramu was now throwing kitchen waste into the compost pit.

"Rohan," Vikram said.

"Don't," Rohan said. "Don't use that tone. The 'elder brother' tone."

He turned back.

His lip was still slightly dark near the corner where the contractor's men had hit him three months ago.

"Everyone at the site knew," Rohan said. "Before I did. The contractor's supervisor came to me at two. He said, 'Ahuja Sahib is serious, you should leave.' He said it like he was giving me a concession."

"He was trying to help."

"He was showing me that even my father's death is company business," Rohan said.

He walked to the desk, his finger tracing the brass lion's mane.

"Seven hundred crore. Fourteen hundred crore. Ten thousand crore. That's what you and Reddy talk about. That's what is written in the papers."

He looked at Vikram properly now.

"Papa died in this house. The house belongs to the company. The car Joshi came in belongs to the company. Even the shroud we will buy today will be billed to the office account."

"Rohan—"

"I don't want it," Rohan said. He spoke louder now, his voice echoing off the high ceiling. "I don't want your charity. I don't want to be the younger brother who was given a site-engineer job to keep him quiet."

"You chose that job yourself."

"Because it was the only one where nobody asked who my brother was!"

A silence followed.

The old ceiling fan in the study gave a low, metallic groan as it turned.

Rohan sat back down.

"He wanted a doctor," Rohan whispered. "He wanted you to wear the white coat. He told me that when I was twelve. 'Vicky will be the doctor.' He said it like I was just the spare."

"He didn't mean that."

"He did," Rohan said. "And then you left the college. You took the office. You took the board. You took the South expansion. You took everything he had to give."

He looked at his hands, at the red dust under his nails.

"And now he is gone."

---

Vikram didn't go to the office the next day.

Or the week after.

He stayed in the house, sitting in the small room off the kitchen.

Reddy came twice.

Sinha came once.

They sat in the drawing room, drank the tea Ramu brought, and talked about the transition.

"We need signatures, Vikram," Reddy said, on the second visit. "The Nandyal plant phase two needs approval. The banks are waiting."

"Ask Rohan to sign," Vikram said.

Reddy laughed. A short, dry sound.

"Rohan? He is an engineer, Vikram. The board won't accept his signature on a financial release."

"They will," Vikram said. "If he owns the shares."

Reddy stopped laughing.

He looked at Vikram's face.

"What are you saying?"

"Prepare the transfer documents," Vikram said. "The shares, the house, the Odisha license. Everything Binay Ahuja left. Transfer it to Rohan."

"You're out of your mind," Reddy said, standing up. "He can't run this. He doesn't know the distributors. He doesn't know the MLA."

"He will learn," Vikram said. "I learned."

---

The lawyer brought the papers on a Friday.

The study room was hot. Ramu had forgotten to turn on the cooler.

Rohan stood near the desk.

He didn't touch the pen.

"Why are you doing this?" Rohan asked.

"Because you want it," Vikram said.

"I didn't ask for a gift."

"It's not a gift," Vikram said. "It's what is yours."

He picked up the pen.

He signed first.

His signature had become neat over ten years, the letters even, the 'A' sharp and clear.

He kept the pen down.

"The driver is waiting outside," Vikram said. "The keys to the city office are on the table."

Rohan looked at the signed papers.

His hand trembled slightly as he picked up the pen to sign below Vikram's name.

He didn't look at his brother.

"Where will you go?"

"Sarita's place," Vikram said. "Near the bypass."

Rohan's pen stopped.

"The AIDS shelter?"

"Yes."

"People will talk, Vikram. They will say I pushed you out."

"Let them," Vikram said. "They have been talking since 1995. It is their business."

He picked up his small leather bag from the floor.

Two shirts.

One trousers.

Nothing else.

He walked out of the study.

He didn't use the main gate.

He walked through the kitchen, passed Ramu who was still sorting cardamoms, and went out of the green side gate.

The road outside was dusty, the afternoon sun direct and sharp.

He didn't call a cab.

He walked toward the bypass, his bag in his left hand, his face toward the heat.

[End of Part 1]
